  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the transaction\n\n2. Specific Statute:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering\n- Penalties can vary based on specific circumstances of the offense\n\n3. Factors Affecting Penalties:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Purpose of the laundering\n- Whether it involves international transactions\n- Prior criminal history\n\n4. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\n5. Potential Sentencing Enhancements:\n- Involvement with specific criminal enterprises\n- Repeat offenses\n- Laundering funds related to certain serious crimes\n\nThese are general legal principles. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, I recommend consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney who can provide personalized guidance.",
